<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06145006 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06145006 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  Domestic automakers reported an increase in auto sales in mid-May -- theirfirst of the year -- but dealers weren't much encouraged by the figures. U.S.sales of North American-made cars and light trucks rose 6.7 percent inmid-May, but the gain came against the mid-May period of 1990, one of theweakest sales periods for all of last year. Nine of the 10 major U.S.automakers on Thursday reported combined car and truck sales for the May 11-20period averaged 29,433 a day, compared with an average of 27,092 during thesame period last year.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  AUTO SALES GAIN FOR FIRST TIME IN '91  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Financial Digest  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Staff and Wire Reports  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910524  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  12D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  101  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday May 24, 199100145006,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>